first time in February of 2006,

00:15:04.320 --> 00:15:08.640
which was the same month
that cartoonist did a cartoon

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:12.310
and inflamed the Middle East and
my trip was promptly canceled

00:15:12.310 --> 00:15:17.150
and I was told I was potentially
never going to be able to come.

00:15:17.150 --> 00:15:19.870
And then the archbishop of Aleppo,
he was the one that was kind

00:15:19.870 --> 00:15:21.190
of bringing me and housing me.

00:15:21.190 --> 00:15:24.060
I was staying with him.

00:15:24.060 --> 00:15:27.130
He called me and said, "I
cannot guarantee your safety.

00:15:27.130 --> 00:15:30.200 position:56%
I have no idea when this will be OK.

00:15:30.200 --> 00:15:32.100
I'll let you know."

00:15:32.100 --> 00:15:34.300
And so I told my wife,
I was just married.

00:15:34.300 --> 00:15:35.840
I've been married a couple months.

00:15:35.840 --> 00:15:37.230
I don't think I'm going to Syria.

00:15:37.230 --> 00:15:40.280
They have riots in the streets.

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:43.010
And then my wife was like, "Great."

00:15:43.010 --> 00:15:44.310
[ Laughter ]

00:15:44.310 --> 00:15:50.770
And so in character to the region,
nine days later I get a call,

00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:53.200
"Everything is totally fine,
you can come next week."

00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:55.170
And I was like, "Wonderful."

00:15:55.170 --> 00:16:04.430
So, I arrive and I was confronted
with an image that was one

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:10.330
of the more life changing images
I've ever seen and it was, one,

00:16:10.330 --> 00:16:12.380
I was an official guest
of the church.

00:16:12.380 --> 00:16:13.680
I didn't know what that meant.

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:17.470
And then, two, no one
came to pick me up.

00:16:17.470 --> 00:16:19.290
So, I'm just at the airport.

00:16:19.290 --> 00:16:23.020
I cannot speak a leak of Arabic
with my bags and a little bit

00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:26.580
of Arabic written down the
address of the archbishop.

00:16:26.580 --> 00:16:28.150
So I'm just standing around,

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:30.020
hopefully someone is
going to let me in.

00:16:30.020 --> 00:16:33.480
And the reason why no
one came to pick up is

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:37.790
because Bishop Yohanna had gone on
television with the Grand Mufti,

00:16:37.790 --> 00:16:41.040
the head of Islam for
Syria, Mufti Hassoun

00:16:41.040 --> 00:16:47.990
and together they were denouncing
the riots together in unity

00:16:47.990 --> 00:16:50.610
and it was broadcast on television.

00:16:50.610 --> 00:16:55.880
They were standing side by side
and it was so striking to me

00:16:55.880 --> 00:17:03.400
that this dual attack of
pluralism was something

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:05.190
that was on national television.

00:17:05.190 --> 00:17:07.310
It doesn't happen in
a lot of places.

00:17:07.310 --> 00:17:09.380
And it was very, very interesting.

00:17:09.380 --> 00:17:14.100
And so that was set the tone for
my entire experience in Syria,

00:17:14.100 --> 00:17:21.050
all these extremely delicate
centuries old relationships back

00:17:21.050 --> 00:17:23.320
and forth and it was
really incredible.

00:17:23.320 --> 00:17:26.660
And to be honest as I said,
you know, I'm a punk drummer.

00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:30.960
I know zero about the
history of Syria

00:17:30.960 --> 00:17:33.160
at the beginning of all of this.

00:17:33.160 --> 00:17:37.230
And so the first couple
trips is just me

00:17:37.230 --> 00:17:41.440
by osmosis absorbing the
culture, listening to everything,

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:45.580 position:56%
kind of spending time, a lot of time
with this much people as possible.

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:50.160
And after that first trip in
2006, then I had to get permission

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:52.130
from the Syrian government.

00:17:52.130 --> 00:17:55.220
Not a big deal as someone
that's not a diplomat

00:17:55.220 --> 00:17:58.970
or any experience politically,
whatsoever.

00:17:58.970 --> 00:18:02.130
So I put my proposal together,

00:18:02.130 --> 00:18:05.340
fax to Syrian embassy
and called, "Hello.

00:18:05.340 --> 00:18:06.640
This is Jason Hamacher.

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:11.610 position:56%
Do you get a chance to review my
proposal for this project in Syria?"

00:18:11.610 --> 00:18:13.500
"No, we haven't."

00:18:13.500 --> 00:18:16.330
"OK. When can I call
back to confirm?"

00:18:16.330 --> 00:18:17.630
Two weeks.

00:18:17.630 --> 00:18:19.630
And I called every
two weeks for months

00:18:19.630 --> 00:18:23.970
and months and months and months.

00:18:23.970 --> 00:18:27.710
And then a political
scenario happened.

00:18:27.710 --> 00:18:33.210
Hezbollah and Israel started
fighting each other and I, again,

00:18:33.210 --> 00:18:36.650
not understanding how
sensitive that makes the region.

00:18:36.650 --> 00:18:40.310
I called and I said, hey, at
this point we're all first name.

00:18:40.310 --> 00:18:41.610
"Jason, how are you?"

00:18:41.610 --> 00:18:43.690
"Pretty good.

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:45.460
Get a chance to review
that proposal?"

00:18:45.460 --> 00:18:47.410
"No, we haven't."

00:18:47.410 --> 00:18:50.600
OK. In the very amount of
fact they not condescending,

00:18:50.600 --> 00:18:52.650
the woman that answer
the phone goes,

00:18:52.650 --> 00:18:55.530
"Have you been paying
attention to the news?"

00:18:55.530 --> 00:18:57.940
I was like, "Absolutely."

00:18:57.940 --> 00:19:02.670
"So you know that Israel and
Hezbollah are kind of fighting."

00:19:02.670 --> 00:19:04.430
I said, "Oh, yes, yeah."

00:19:04.430 --> 00:19:08.630
"So, which means that we are on
high alert and I have no idea

00:19:08.630 --> 00:19:12.710
when anyone is going to be
able to review your proposal."

00:19:12.710 --> 00:19:15.520
I said, "I totally understand."

00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:18.320
And this is verbatim what I said,

00:19:18.320 --> 00:19:21.920
"I'll call back when
the war is over."

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:24.300
As it fell out of my mouth,

00:19:24.300 --> 00:19:28.050
I realized I was never
going to return to Syria.

00:19:28.050 --> 00:19:33.010
I was completely embarrassed
and the woman just goes, "OK."

00:19:33.010 --> 00:19:34.310
[ Laughter ]

00:19:34.310 --> 00:19:36.660
And so that was it.

00:19:36.660 --> 00:19:37.960
It was over.

00:19:37.960 --> 00:19:40.640
You know, I knew that that was
just completely embarrassing.

00:19:40.640 --> 00:19:42.580
I would never be able to go.

00:19:42.580 --> 00:19:43.880
And so I just-- I don't know.

00:19:43.880 --> 00:19:46.420
I got to go one time and
see all of these things

00:19:46.420 --> 00:19:48.360
and have all these
really nice photos

00:19:48.360 --> 00:19:51.700
and then two weeks later I
got a call from the embassy

00:19:51.700 --> 00:19:56.750
where someone had read my proposal
by accident and he's father--

00:19:56.750 --> 00:20:01.230
one of his fathers best
friends attended this one church

00:20:01.230 --> 00:20:05.510
in the one neighborhood in Aleppo
and had just past away and he went

00:20:05.510 --> 00:20:08.020
to his funeral and the son went.

00:20:08.020 --> 00:20:13.020
And so he was like, "Yeah, I heard
this amazing chant at this funeral

00:20:13.020 --> 00:20:17.620
and then I came back to work
and found the proposal trying

00:20:17.620 --> 00:20:19.390
to record it on someone's desk."

00:20:19.390 --> 00:20:20.720
He's like, "Is this you?"

00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:22.770
I was like, "Yes."

00:20:22.770 --> 00:20:25.010
He's like, "When can you come in
and meet with the ambassador?"

00:20:25.010 --> 00:20:26.810
I was like, "Whenever
you want me to."

00:20:26.810 --> 00:20:31.800
And so, that's what led to the next
several phases of this project,

00:20:31.800 --> 00:20:36.260
the former ambassador from Syria
to United States invited me over

00:20:36.260 --> 00:20:39.010
and because I'm, you
know, a lone wolf.

00:20:39.010 --> 00:20:43.330
I'm not official journalist
or representing anyone other

00:20:43.330 --> 00:20:45.520
than the sake of preservation.

00:20:45.520 --> 00:20:49.450
He kind of green-lit all
my ideas and then one

00:20:49.450 --> 00:20:51.360
of the components was I wanted

00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:55.570
to photograph extensively
these older neighborhoods

00:20:55.570 --> 00:20:57.650
in the City of Aleppo.

00:20:57.650 --> 00:21:01.680
And I'll be showing you a lot
of these photographs later.

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:03.790 position:56%
And he's like, "I'm a big art's fan.

00:21:03.790 --> 00:21:05.360
I'd love to see your photography."

00:21:05.360 --> 00:21:08.120
I was like, "I didn't
bring any with me."

00:21:08.120 --> 00:21:13.030
And so I was invited back
and I showed him my vision

00:21:13.030 --> 00:21:18.360 position:56%
of my first trip and he kind of
tasked me to make a book on the City

00:21:18.360 --> 00:21:19.910
of Aleppo and that's
something I've been working

00:21:19.910 --> 00:21:23.140
on for the last eight years.

00:21:23.140 --> 00:21:28.450
And, at this point, I always
like to say I was never paid

00:21:28.450 --> 00:21:33.290 position:56%
by the Syrian government in any
way, shape or form to do any of this

00:21:33.290 --> 00:21:35.360
but far more valuable
for those of you

00:21:35.360 --> 00:21:39.250
that are know, he cut
all the red tape.

00:21:39.250 --> 00:21:44.630
So, I was given inside access to
all these places inside the city

00:21:44.630 --> 00:21:47.350
that most Syrians don't
ever get to see.

00:21:47.350 --> 00:21:50.710
And so over the years, things
developed, things developed

00:21:50.710 --> 00:21:56.350
and then I made my actual
first recordings in 2008

00:21:56.350 --> 00:21:58.210
and this is what it sounds like.

00:21:58.210 --> 00:22:03.430
So this-- now, I'm going
to explain why I do this

00:22:03.430 --> 00:22:05.760
on record in a little bit.

00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:09.900
So this is called "Holy
are you God".

00:22:09.900 --> 00:22:13.990
It is from the ancient
tradition of Edessa and this is

00:22:13.990 --> 00:22:18.140
from that little neighborhood
inside Aleppo.

00:22:21.510 --> 00:25:32.240
[ Singing ]

00:25:32.240 --> 00:25:40.690
So at the time of that
recording which is 2008,

00:25:40.690 --> 00:25:43.940
five people on the planet
were the masters of this.

00:25:43.940 --> 00:25:46.530
That's dramatically dropped.

00:25:46.530 --> 00:25:48.090
Dramatically there are five.

00:25:48.090 --> 00:25:51.400
There are now three
since this recording.

00:25:51.400 --> 00:25:52.930
So that was in 2008.

00:25:52.930 --> 00:25:55.590
Those recordings will
be in production

00:25:55.590 --> 00:25:58.230
with Smithsonian Folkways.

00:25:58.230 --> 00:26:01.370
This album has been in
production for 10 years.

00:26:01.370 --> 00:26:04.660
Hopefully, it will come out
within the next year or so.

00:26:04.660 --> 00:26:11.900
But, on that first trip in
2006, every single minute

00:26:11.900 --> 00:26:13.600
of my time was accounted for.

00:26:13.600 --> 00:26:16.950
You know, the archbishop had
me doing everything with him.

00:26:16.950 --> 00:26:21.330
One day he had me sit and
remember I cannot speak any Arabic.

00:26:21.330 --> 00:26:25.570
I just sat down and he wanted
me to kind of photograph

00:26:25.570 --> 00:26:28.500
and see what his day looked
like in the day of meetings.

00:26:28.500 --> 00:26:32.040
So, there's a big kind of
grandiose hall, about half the size

00:26:32.040 --> 00:26:36.250
of this room, just as high
ceilings and I just sat on the side

00:26:36.250 --> 00:26:38.630
and people came in and out all day.

00:26:38.630 --> 00:26:44.150
And the first person that came in
was an elderly widow who was asking

00:26:44.150 --> 00:26:46.630
for assistance to just
keep her house

00:26:46.630 --> 00:26:49.250
because she couldn't
afford it anymore.

00:26:49.250 --> 00:26:53.250
One was a businessman who was
coming in to plan financially.

00:26:53.250 --> 00:26:58.630 position:56%
They were building a hospital in one
of the suburbs which you can now see

00:26:58.630 --> 00:27:03.770
on YouTube, just being
totally decimated.

00:27:03.770 --> 00:27:06.960
To the highlight of the day
was the Prince of Greece.

00:27:06.960 --> 00:27:13.680 position:56%
The Prince of Greece came in who
was his sister is the Queen of Spain

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:18.760
and the bishop thought it was
really funny always to make me all

00:27:18.760 --> 00:27:22.310
of a sudden launch into, "Jason,
this is the Prince of Greece.

00:27:22.310 --> 00:27:23.850
Tell him what you're doing."

00:27:23.850 --> 00:27:29.450
I was like, "What do I"--
I was like, "Forgive me.

00:27:29.450 --> 00:27:30.750
What do I call you?"

00:27:30.750 --> 00:27:32.340
I'm like, "Is it your highness?

00:27:32.340 --> 00:27:33.640
What do I?"

00:27:33.640 --> 00:27:34.940
He's like, "I'm Prince Michael."

00:27:34.940 --> 00:27:37.070
I was like, "Prince Michael" and
then yeah, I go into these things.

00:27:37.070 --> 00:27:39.800
And so it was back and
forth and during the course

00:27:39.800 --> 00:27:45.620 position:56%
of this six hour extent of meetings,
this elderly man walked in kind

00:27:45.620 --> 00:27:49.690
of unannounced and it looked
like he was lost, to be honest.

00:27:49.690 --> 00:27:52.420
He just kind of sat down
and we're sitting there

00:27:52.420 --> 00:27:55.830
and the bishop was speaking
and he broke and just goes,

00:27:55.830 --> 00:27:59.210
"This is the leader of the
last Jewish family in the North

00:27:59.210 --> 00:28:01.030 position:56%
of Syria," and he just kept talking.

00:28:01.030 --> 00:28:02.840
I was like, "What?"

00:28:02.840 --> 00:28:06.260
And so, I was, "Yeah,
nice to meet you.

00:28:06.260 --> 00:28:08.490
How are you?"

00:28:08.490 --> 00:28:09.790
And so-- well someone had told me

00:28:09.790 --> 00:28:13.340 position:56%
that there is this amazing
historical synagogue inside the city

00:28:13.340 --> 00:28:18.800
and afterwards I asked
him about the synagogue.

00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:24.040 position:56%
And, someone's remote control car
is going out of control in the back.

00:28:24.040 --> 00:28:25.340
Is my son here?

00:28:25.340 --> 00:28:26.990
He's three.

00:28:26.990 --> 00:28:32.460
So essentially, the-- I
asked him about the synagogue

00:28:32.460 --> 00:28:36.640
and not recognizing the
weight of an official guest.

00:28:36.640 --> 00:28:41.120
He felt complied-- compelled to
take me inside the synagogue.

00:28:41.120 --> 00:28:45.870
So, in 2006, I got to go in the
ancient synagogue of Aleppo.

00:28:45.870 --> 00:28:48.160
The foundation has been
traditionally held.

00:28:48.160 --> 00:28:50.730 position:56%
It was built by King David's general

00:28:50.730 --> 00:28:55.680
and the current structure is the
oldest continual used structure

00:28:55.680 --> 00:28:57.870
in the entire City of Aleppo.

00:28:57.870 --> 00:29:01.760
Meaning, it was never destroyed
and rebuilt-- I take that back.

00:29:01.760 --> 00:29:03.780
It was never repurposed.

00:29:03.780 --> 00:29:08.910
Meaning, it's 1600 years old in the
dead center of town and that leads

00:29:08.910 --> 00:29:13.920
to the second phase of
my experiences in Syria

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:17.520
which was I ended up doing
a photo exhibit here in DC.

00:29:17.520 --> 00:29:20.910
at the JCC on '16th
of the synagogue.

00:29:20.910 --> 00:29:27.810
A synagogue exhibit, which led to
me working with a Jewish museum,

00:29:27.810 --> 00:29:33.080
that's not open yet in New York as
their documentarian and explorer

00:29:33.080 --> 00:29:37.640
for all of the Jewish
properties in all of Syria

00:29:37.640 --> 00:29:42.790
and the project was the photograph
document and assess what was there,

00:29:42.790 --> 00:29:46.150
what's left, what is everything.

00:29:46.150 --> 00:29:50.290
And so, I did that
in 2008, '9 and '10.

00:29:50.290 --> 00:29:56.570
2010, unannounced the
government support

00:29:56.570 --> 00:29:59.000
for that project was totally bold.

00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:01.220 position:56%
So I showed up and I was not allowed

00:30:01.220 --> 00:30:04.040
in to anything that
was Jewish anymore.

00:30:04.040 --> 00:30:05.640
I was allowed to go.

00:30:05.640 --> 00:30:08.950
I could bring all my
equipment but I couldn't go in.

00:30:08.950 --> 00:30:14.230
And so I had free time
for the first time

00:30:14.230 --> 00:30:16.750
in my six year experience in Syria.

00:30:16.750 --> 00:30:22.030
So I started out of boredom
recording all of the places

00:30:22.030 --> 00:30:24.870
that I used to walk
by, just my walk.

00:30:24.870 --> 00:30:26.970
This is what my day
sounds like in Syria.

00:30:26.970 --> 00:30:32.650
And so, the Forty Martyrs Armenian
Church is located in a neighborhood

00:30:32.650 --> 00:30:35.110
with the best restaurants, right?

00:30:35.110 --> 00:30:38.950
And so I would go there and
that's where I would have lunch.

00:30:38.950 --> 00:30:41.290
There's this place called
CC House or Casa Cavalli.

00:30:41.290 --> 00:30:43.640
You know, you'll see some of
these photos in a little bit.

00:30:43.640 --> 00:30:48.460
And I went in and would asked,
"Hey, I'm-- I've got some time off.

00:30:48.460 --> 00:30:49.970
I'm a guest of the bishop.

00:30:49.970 --> 00:30:52.810
Would you permit me to come
in and make these recordings?"

00:30:52.810 --> 00:30:55.460
So, I made them for no
other reason but just

00:30:55.460 --> 00:30:58.840
to kill time walking
around the ancient city.

00:30:58.840 --> 00:31:06.830
And that was October of
2010 and then I was going

00:31:06.830 --> 00:31:09.820
to return in May of 2011.

00:31:09.820 --> 00:31:12.780
And then, I'll never forget
this I was at Del Chess

00:31:12.780 --> 00:31:16.530
in Dupont Circle talking with a
friend Inash [assumed spelling].

00:31:16.530 --> 00:31:20.060
He was a former diplomat
from the Syrian embassy.

00:31:20.060 --> 00:31:25.180
We were talking about how
insane the Arab spring was

00:31:25.180 --> 00:31:28.100
and we couldn't believe
how it was happening

00:31:28.100 --> 00:31:30.650
and how it would never
happen in Syria,

00:31:30.650 --> 00:31:33.280
neither was ever thought
it would happen.

00:31:33.280 --> 00:31:40.890
And then, I think it was nine days
later it kicked in and it happened.

00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:44.420
and I was in shock as most people.

00:31:44.420 --> 00:31:49.780
A part of my shock was not because
of what was happening but was

00:31:49.780 --> 00:31:53.740
for the first time in my life, I
was connected to a world event.

00:31:53.740 --> 00:31:55.840
That's not something music related.

00:31:55.840 --> 00:32:00.590
You know my music community is
real small and it's influential

00:32:00.590 --> 00:32:03.550
but it's not world news
in any way, shape or form.

00:32:03.550 --> 00:32:07.950
And so all of a sudden--
and I just become a father.

00:32:07.950 --> 00:32:11.180
So I have-- at this point,
I'm totally sleep wrecked

00:32:11.180 --> 00:32:15.790
because I've got a daughter that's
weeks old and the war has kicked in

00:32:15.790 --> 00:32:20.820
and this Smithsonian has
officially accepted the project

00:32:20.820 --> 00:32:23.770
and it just keeps getting worse.

00:32:23.770 --> 00:32:27.500
And so, in my little Facebook feed,

00:32:27.500 --> 00:32:29.720
all of a sudden I'm
getting commercials

00:32:29.720 --> 00:32:34.530
for Syria related things,
"Oh, you've typed Syria in.

00:32:34.530 --> 00:32:38.420 position:56%
You would be interested in buying
this or buying that," and it started

00:32:38.420 --> 00:32:40.600
to disgust me, to be honest.

00:32:40.600 --> 00:32:45.340
That, all of the sudden,
no one had cared anything.

00:32:45.340 --> 00:32:47.850
Like, I would try to tell
people, "Hey, I'm going to Syria."

00:32:47.850 --> 00:32:49.390
Like, "That's cool.

00:32:49.390 --> 00:32:51.090 position:56%
What else-- tell me something else?"

00:32:51.090 --> 00:32:55.250
And so all of the sudden that,
there's destruction happening.

00:32:55.250 --> 00:32:59.640
Now it's considered commercially
viable and I'm getting ads

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:01.790
about this on the computer.

00:33:01.790 --> 00:33:04.910
So, I stopped working on
everything, to be honest,

00:33:04.910 --> 00:33:10.140
in solidarity for what's
still happening.

00:33:10.140 --> 00:33:13.400
And so, I stopped working
on the book.

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:16.580
I stopped working on the
albums and all of this

00:33:16.580 --> 00:33:20.590
and then it just kept worse and
getting worse and getting worse

00:33:20.590 --> 00:33:25.170
and then it came up North
and then it was in Aleppo.

00:33:25.170 --> 00:33:29.510 position:56%
And, now all of the sudden, at first
it was kind of mentioned everyone,

00:33:29.510 --> 00:33:34.740 position:56%
